@article{Friedland1995-vi,
abstract = {Organisms on wave-swept intertidal shores often must withstand
water velocities of 10 to 20 m/s and accompanying accelerations
of 400 m/s'. Because drag and accelerational forces increase with
area and volume respectively, the bigger an individual is, the
larger the forces on it become. This size-force relationship
suggests that large intertidal algae must be particularly well
designed if they are to survive. The feather boa kelp, Egregiu
menziesii (Turner), grows to a size that is unusually large for
its wave-exposed habitat, leading us to inquire into the
mechanisms that allow it to attain this stature. A
hydro-mechanical computer model is used to predict the magnitude
of the forces on E. menziesii in various wave conditions and for
various plant sizes. Based on measurements of the strength of E.
